    <text>
        <body>
            <head>280. Memorandum From Secretary of State <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN"
                    >Shultz</persName> to President <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq"
                    >Reagan</persName>
                <note n="1" place="foot" type="source" xml:id="d280fn1">Source: Reagan Library,
                        <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName> Papers. Memorandum
                    for the President (02/09/1988–03/10/1988). Secret; Sensitive. Drafted by
                        <persName corresp="recVITvpjZsQaZWYz">Parris</persName>; cleared by
                        <persName corresp="reccVKFbVuxnI4007">Ridgway</persName>.</note>
            </head>
            <opener>
                <dateline rendition="#right">
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1988-03-10"
                        >March 10, 1988</date>
                </dateline>
            </opener>
            <list type="subject">
                <head>SUBJECT</head>
                <item>Message from <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>
                </item>
            </list>
            <p>Ambassador <persName corresp="rec8Ijb8Ggcq23rmf">Dubinin</persName> came by
                    Thursday<note n="2" place="foot" xml:id="d280fn2">March 10.</note> to deliver a
                letter from <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName>, which
                incorporated <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName>’s response
                to the message you sent him from Brussels on <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss>.<note n="3" place="foot" xml:id="d280fn3">See <ref target="#d279">Document
                        279</ref>.</note>
            </p>
            <p>I have attached the text of <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl"
                    >Gorbachev</persName>’s message, which seconds your view that our primary
                objective should be to get a good <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                    <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                </gloss> agreement. He expresses confidence that this can be accomplished by the
                time of your visit to Moscow, and indicates that the Soviet bureaucracy has recently
                been told, in effect, to “go for the gold.” This may explain the movement we have
                seen over the past week in Geneva.</p>
            <p>I took the opportunity to ask <persName corresp="rec8Ijb8Ggcq23rmf"
                    >Dubinin</persName> if he thought <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc"
                    >Shevardnadze</persName> would be bringing dates for the <rs type="event"
                    corresp="recHp9uQv5w7SafI2">Moscow summit</rs>. He said he had no reason to
                believe there had been any change from what <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc"
                    >Shevardnadze</persName> had said publicly at the close of my February visit to
                Moscow—that he expected to set dates during his trip here this month.</p>
            <pb facs="1273" n="1246" xml:id="pg_1246"/>
            <frus:attachment xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0">
                <note>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Attachment</hi>
                </note>
                <head>
                    <hi rendition="simple_bold">Message From Soviet Secretary General <persName
                            corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl">Gorbachev</persName> to President <persName
                            corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Reagan</persName>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="4" place="foot" xml:id="d280fn4">Secret.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Moscow</placeName>, <date
                            ana="#date_undated-inferred-from-editorial-annotation"
                            calendar="gregorian" when="1988-03-10">undated</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rendition="simple_centre">
                    <hi rendition="simple_italic">Text of <persName corresp="recXTrNyt2vU9QpAl"
                            >Gorbachev</persName> Message</hi>
                    <note n="5" place="foot" xml:id="d280fn5">Conveyed in a letter form Foreign
                        Minister <persName corresp="reczYQHQnMCD2hSLc">Shevardnadze</persName> to
                        Secretary <persName corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">Shultz</persName>, dated
                        March 10, 1988, and delivered by Ambassador <persName
                            corresp="rec8Ijb8Ggcq23rmf">Dubinin</persName> to <persName
                            corresp="rece7NCQ7Hh9DICyN">the Secretary</persName> on that date.
                        [Footnote is in the original.]</note>
                </p>
                <p>The Soviet leadership have carefully examined your considerations concerning the
                    conclusion of the <gloss target="#t_START_1">
                        <rs type="event" corresp="recGzN4S83GSdMO7O">START</rs>
                    </gloss>
                    <rs type="agreement-or-mandate" corresp="recHvtjt4uCqCi2Qk">Treaty</rs>. We in
                    Moscow share the hope that despite all the difficulties that are, as both of us
                    are well aware, involved in its preparation, this new, important agreement will
                    be concluded in the course of your visit to the U.S.S.R. We agree with you that
                    above all we need a good agreement, that is, one that meets the interests of
                    both sides and fully takes into account their security concerns, as well as the
                    broader objectives of enhancing international stability. We are confident that,
                    given the necessary political will on both sides, this task can be accomplished
                    by the forthcoming Soviet—U.S. summit meeting.</p>
                <p>Recently we held a special meeting in Moscow with our diplomatic and military
                    representatives, at which they were given appropriate instructions.</p>
                <p>We are convinced, <persName corresp="rec5PPNCl6qqfgBAq">Mr. President</persName>,
                    that our two countries now have a realistic possibility to have your visit to
                    Moscow marked by taking another major joint step toward reducing the risks of
                    nuclear war.</p>
            </frus:attachment>
        </body>
    </text>
